  {
    id: 4, title: "Inconsistency", subtitle: "Когда исследования расходятся во мнениях", xp: 160,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "orange-bg", content: { title: "Inconsistency", subtitle: "Вторая область: что нам делать, если исследования расходятся во мнениях?" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Поймите, почему результаты исследований различаются и когда различия вызывают беспокойство.",
          "Интерпретируйте статистику I² и тау² для неоднородности.",
          "Distinguish explainable from unexplainable inconsistency",
          "Decide when to downgrade certainty for inconsistency"
        ],
        tip: "Real disagreement between studies tells us something important."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Противоречие с витамином D", title: "Когда 200 исследований не смогли прийти к единому мнению",
        text: "By 2019, over <strong>200 randomized trials</strong> had studied vitamin D supplementation. The results were chaos. Some showed vitamin D prevented cancer (RR 0.77). Others showed no effect (RR 1.02). Some showed harm (RR 1.15). Meta-analyses pooled them all and proclaimed 'statistically significant benefit.' But the I² was <strong>78%</strong>—massive heterogeneity that the summary estimate concealed.",
        followup: "The largest trial, VITAL (25,871 participants), finally brought clarity. It showed <strong>no benefit</strong> for cancer or cardiovascular disease. The smaller positive studies had methodological problems: inadequate randomization, post-hoc analyses, selected populations. The pooled estimate had hidden a crucial truth: when studies wildly disagree, the average may represent no one's truth. GRADE requires downgrading for this kind of inconsistency, regardless of what the pooled estimate shows."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📊", title: "Сценарий: гетерогенный метаанализ",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis of 15 trials shows pooled benefit (OR 0.75, p<0.001). However, I² = 82%, tau² is large, and the prediction interval crosses 1.0. Six trials show harm, nine show benefit. The authors conclude 'significant benefit with moderate heterogeneity.'",
        question: "How should inconsistency affect the certainty rating?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No downgrade—the pooled estimate is statistically significant", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Downgrade one level—I² > 75% is substantial heterogeneity", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Downgrade one or two levels—prediction interval crossing 1.0 means future studies might show harm", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot rate—inconsistent evidence is uninterpretable", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The prediction interval is key. When it crosses the null, we're saying: 'If we did another study, it might show the opposite effect.' That's profound uncertainty. I² = 82% with a prediction interval crossing 1.0 warrants serious downgrading.",
          incorrect: "I², равный 82%, означает сильную неоднородность, но интервал прогнозирования более информативен. Превышение значения 1,0 означает, что будущие исследования могут показать вред — совокупная «польза» может не распространяться на следующего пациента. Статистическая значимость объединенной оценки не спасает противоречивые данные."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Тайна инсульта", title: "Aspirin's Vanishing Benefit",
        text: "In 1988, the ISIS-2 trial proved aspirin reduced death after heart attack by <strong>23%</strong>. The evidence was bulletproof—17,187 patients, clear benefit, minimal heterogeneity when pooled with similar trials. Aspirin became standard care.",
        followup: "But stroke prevention was different. Meta-analyses of aspirin for primary prevention showed <strong>wildly inconsistent results</strong>. Some trials showed 15% reduction in stroke. Others showed 10% increase. The I² exceeded 60%. The explanation emerged slowly: aspirin prevents <strong>ischemic</strong> stroke but causes <strong>hemorrhagic</strong> stroke. When trials measured 'all stroke,' results depended on the baseline mix of stroke types in each population. The inconsistency wasn't noise—it was biology. Understanding <em>why</em> studies differ changes interpretation entirely."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔍", title: "Сценарий: объяснимое несоответствие",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis shows I² = 70%. However, subgroup analysis reveals: trials in high-risk patients show consistent benefit (I² = 15%, OR 0.60), while trials in low-risk patients show consistent null effects (I² = 20%, OR 1.02). The high I² is entirely explained by mixing these populations.",
        question: "Стоит ли понижать рейтинг из-за несоответствия?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Yes—I² = 70% always requires downgrading", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—inconsistency is fully explained by a pre-specified, biologically plausible subgroup", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Partially—downgrade one level despite the explanation", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Report two separate certainty ratings for each subgroup", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Правильный! GRADE отличает необъяснимую гетерогенность (понижение рейтинга) от гетерогенности, полностью объясняемой вероятными эффектами подгруппы (нет понижения рейтинга из-за несоответствия). Объяснение должно быть заранее определенным и биологически правдоподобным, а не апостериорным сбором данных.",
          incorrect: "When heterogeneity is fully explained by a pre-specified, credible subgroup effect, the 'inconsistency' actually tells us something useful: treatment works differently in different populations. This informs clinical practice rather than undermining certainty."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Альбуминовый парадокс", title: "28 Trials, Zero Answers",
        text: "Should critically ill patients receive albumin for fluid resuscitation? By 1998, the Cochrane Injuries Group had pooled <strong>28 trials</strong>. Their conclusion: albumin <strong>increases mortality by 68%</strong> (RR 1.68). Headlines screamed. NHS considered banning albumin. The evidence seemed damning.",
        followup: "But look closer at those 28 trials. I² was <strong>0%</strong>—no heterogeneity. A different problem lurked: the trials were tiny (many with <50 patients), measured different populations (burns, trauma, surgery), and many were decades old. The <strong>SAFE trial</strong> (6,997 patients, 2004) finally answered the question: albumin was <strong>equivalent to saline</strong>—no benefit, no harm. The pooled estimate from 28 small, disparate trials had been an artifact of random variation in underpowered studies, not a real signal. Consistency (low I²) doesn't guarantee truth."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚖️", title: "Сценарий: Последовательные, но тревожные доказательства",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis pools 12 small trials (total n=400) with I² = 5%—very low heterogeneity. The pooled effect is OR 0.50 (dramatic benefit), statistically significant. A colleague argues this deserves HIGH certainty because results are 'beautifully consistent.'",
        question: "What concern should you raise?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "None—low I² means high certainty for inconsistency", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Low I² in small trials may reflect consistent bias, not consistent truth", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "I² = 5% is too low and suggests publication bias", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "The pooled estimate is too dramatic to be real", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Правильный! Небольшие испытания с последовательными впечатляющими результатами должны вызвать подозрения. У них могут быть одни и те же предубеждения (предвзятость публикаций, схожие ошибочные методы). Мета-анализ альбумина показал I² около 0% в 28 исследованиях, но крупное исследование SAFE показало нулевой эффект. Последовательность в небольших испытаниях ≠ истина.",
          incorrect: "Low heterogeneity among small, potentially biased trials can be misleading. If all trials share similar biases (publication bias, poor methods), they'll show consistently biased results. The albumin case proves this: I² was low, but the effect was an artifact."
        }
      }},
      { type: "stats", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Understanding I² Thresholds",
        stats: [
          { value: "0-25%", label: "Low heterogeneity" },
          { value: "25-50%", label: "Moderate" },
          { value: "50-75%", label: "Substantial" },
          { value: ">75%", label: "Considerable" }
        ],
        caption: "Но сам по себе I² не определяет понижение рейтинга — большее значение имеют интервал прогнозирования и клиническое значение."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Inconsistency Assessment Checklist",
        items: [
          "Calculate I² and tau² — but don't stop there",
          "Examine prediction interval — does it cross clinically important thresholds?",
          "Ищите перекрывающиеся доверительные интервалы между исследованиями.",
          "Check if heterogeneity can be explained by credible subgroups",
          "Consider if small trials are driving inconsistency (vs. large trial disagreement)"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Почему интервал прогнозирования более важен, чем I², для оценки несоответствия GRADE?",
        options: [
          { text: "Prediction intervals are easier to calculate", correct: false },
          { text: "Prediction intervals tell us what effect a future study might show", correct: true },
          { text: "I² is only valid for large meta-analyses", correct: false },
          { text: "Prediction intervals account for publication bias", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Exactly. The prediction interval says: 'The next study from this distribution of effects will probably fall in this range.' If that range includes harm while the pooled estimate shows benefit, we're deeply uncertain about what will happen to the next patient.",
          incorrect: "The prediction interval captures uncertainty about what future studies (or the next patient) might experience. I² tells us whether heterogeneity exists; the prediction interval tells us whether it matters clinically."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 5, title: "Indirectness", subtitle: "Неправильный вопрос, неправильный ответ", xp: 170,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "purple-bg", content: { title: "Indirectness", subtitle: "Третий домен: отвечают ли эти доказательства на наш актуальный вопрос?" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Recognize four types of indirectness: population, intervention, comparator, outcome",
          "Understand why surrogate outcomes mislead",
          "Apply indirectness assessment to real scenarios",
          "Decide when evidence is too indirect to trust"
        ],
        tip: "Лучшим доказательством неправильного вопроса по-прежнему является неправильный ответ."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Катастрофа CAST", title: "50 000 погибших от логического лечения",
        text: "After a heart attack, arrhythmias predict death. <strong>Encainide and flecainide</strong> suppressed arrhythmias on ECG beautifully—85% reduction in premature ventricular contractions. The FDA approved them. Cardiologists prescribed them to hundreds of thousands of post-MI patients. The logic was irresistible: dangerous arrhythmias → sudden death; suppress arrhythmias → prevent death.",
        followup: "The CAST trial was designed to confirm what everyone already 'knew.' Instead, it delivered a verdict that stunned cardiology. Patients on anti-arrhythmic drugs died at <strong>3.6 times the rate</strong> of placebo. The trials were stopped early for harm. An estimated <strong>50,000 Americans died</strong> from drugs that perfectly fixed the surrogate (ECG) while causing the outcome (death). The evidence for arrhythmia suppression was HIGH certainty—but it was indirect evidence for mortality. That indirectness killed 50,000 people."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
