        text: "In 1950, Richard Doll and Austin Bradford Hill published their case-control study: smokers had <strong>30 times higher lung cancer rates</strong> than non-smokers. The tobacco industry demanded RCTs—knowing they were impossible. 'Correlation isn't causation,' they insisted. 'Where's the randomized evidence?'",
        followup: "But the effect size spoke for itself. For confounding to explain a 30-fold increase, some unmeasured factor would need to cause both smoking and lung cancer with extraordinary strength—and be distributed perfectly across populations, generations, and geographies. No such confounder has ever been found. The evidence was upgraded from LOW to HIGH. GRADE recognizes that some effects are too large for confounding to explain."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
